is.hello.go99.animators

Class MultiAnimator

  • java.lang.Object
    • android.animation.Animator
      • is.hello.go99.animators.MultiAnimator
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    android.animation.Animator.AnimatorListener, java.lang.Cloneable

    @NotBindable
public class MultiAnimator
extends android.animation.Animator
implements android.animation.Animator.AnimatorListener
    A wrapper around ViewPropertyAnimator that descends from Animator to allow for generic treatment of all animations within an AnimatorContext.

    • Method Detail

      • animatorFor

        public static MultiAnimator animatorFor(android.view.View view)
        Creates a multi-animator for a given view, unbound to any animator context.

        Important: MultiAnimator does not cache view animators, every call to #animatorFor(View) returns a new object. Additionally, attempting to run multiple multi-animators for a single view at the same time will result in undefined behavior.

        Parameters:
        view - The view to create an animator for.
        Returns:
        A new multi-animator object.

      • animatorFor

        public static MultiAnimator animatorFor(android.view.View view,
                                        AnimatorContext animatorContext)
        Creates a multi-animator for a given view, and binds it to a given animator context.

        The transaction template of the animator context will be applied to the multi-animator.

        Important: MultiAnimator does not cache view animators, every call to #animatorFor(View) returns a new object. Additionally, attempting to run multiple multi-animators for a single view at the same time will result in undefined behavior.

        Parameters:
        view - The view to create an animator for.
        animatorContext - The animator context to bind to.
        Returns:
        A new multi-animator object.

      • start

        public void start()
        Description copied from class: android.animation.Animator
        Starts this animation. If the animation has a nonzero startDelay, the animation will start running after that delay elapses. A non-delayed animation will have its initial value(s) set immediately, followed by calls to Animator.AnimatorListener.onAnimationStart(Animator) for any listeners of this animator.

        The animation started by calling this method will be run on the thread that called this method. This thread should have a Looper on it (a runtime exception will be thrown if this is not the case). Also, if the animation will animate properties of objects in the view hierarchy, then the calling thread should be the UI thread for that view hierarchy.

        Overrides:
        start in class android.animation.Animator

      • postStart

      • cancel

        public void cancel()
        Description copied from class: android.animation.Animator
        Cancels the animation. Unlike Animator.end(), cancel() causes the animation to stop in its tracks, sending an Animator.AnimatorListener.onAnimationCancel(Animator) to its listeners, followed by an Animator.AnimatorListener.onAnimationEnd(Animator) message.

        This method must be called on the thread that is running the animation.

        Overrides:
        cancel in class android.animation.Animator

      • end

        public void end()
        Description copied from class: android.animation.Animator
        Ends the animation. This causes the animation to assign the end value of the property being animated, then calling the Animator.AnimatorListener.onAnimationEnd(Animator) method on its listeners.

        This method must be called on the thread that is running the animation.

        Overrides:
        end in class android.animation.Animator
